# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: honeypot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology considers the point of view of human attackers and method for exploiting and navigating networks to identify and exfiltrate data.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] It integrates with existing technologies to provide new visibility into the internal networks, share high probability alerts and threat intelligence with the existing infrastructure.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology automates the creation of traps (decoys) and lures, which are strategically integrated among existing IT resources.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] These decoys provide an additional layer of protection to thwart attackers who have breached the network.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Traps can be IT assets that utilize genuine licensed operating system software or emulate various devices, such as medical devices, automated teller machines (ATMs), retail point-of-sale systems, switches, routers, and more.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] On the other hand, lures typically consist of real information technology resources, such as files of different types, that are placed on actual IT assets.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Due to advancement in the area of cybersecurity, deception technology programs are increasingly proactive in approach and produce fewer false-positive alerts.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] The goal is to accurately discover the intention of the attacker and their tactics, technique and procedure.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] These information will enable effective response from the deception technology platforms.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Upon penetrating the network, attackers seek to establish a backdoor and then use this to identify and exfiltrate data and intellectual property.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] They begin moving laterally through the internal VLANs and almost immediately will "encounter" one of the traps.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Interacting with one of these "decoys" will trigger an alert.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] These alerts have very high probability and almost always coincide to an ongoing attack.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] The deception is designed to lure the attacker in – the attacker may consider this a worthy asset and continue by injecting malware.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology generally allows for automated static and dynamic analysis of this injected malware and provides these reports through automation to the security operations personnel.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology may also identify, through indicators of compromise (IOC), suspect end-points that are part of the compromise cycle.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Automation also allows for an automated memory analysis of the suspect endpoints, and then automatically isolating the suspect endpoints.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Internet of things (IoT) devices are not usually scanned by legacy defense in depth and remain prime targets for attackers within the network.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology can identify attackers moving laterally into the network within these devices.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Integrated turnkey devices that utilize embedded operating systems but do not allow these operating systems to be scanned or closely protected by embedded end-point or intrusion detection software are also well protected by a deception technology deployment in the same network.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Examples include process control systems (SCADA) used in many manufacturing applications on a global basis.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology has been associated with the discovery of Zombie Zero, an attack vector.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology identified this attacker utilizing malware embedded in barcode readers which were manufactured overseas.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Medical devices are particular vulnerable to cyber-attacks within the healthcare networks.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] As FDA-certified devices, they are in closed systems and not accessible to standard cyber defense software.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology can surround and protect these devices and identify attackers using backdoor placement and data exfiltration.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Recent documented cyber attacks on medical devices include x-ray machines, CT scanners, MRI scanners, blood gas analyzers, PACS systems and many more.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Networks utilizing these devices can be protected by deception technology.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] This attack vector, called medical device hijack or medjack, is estimated to have penetrated many hospitals worldwide.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Specialized deception technology products are now capable of addressing the rise in ransomware by deceiving ransomware into engaging in an attack on a decoy resource, while isolating the infection points and alerting the cyber defense software team.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Honeypots were perhaps the first very simple form of deception.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] A honeypot appeared simply as an unprotected information technology resource and presented itself in an attractive way to a prospective attacker already within the network.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] However, most early honeypots exhibit challenges with functionality, integrity and overall efficacy in meeting these goals.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] A key difficulty was lack of automation that enabled broad scale deployment; a deployment strategy that aimed to cover an enterprise where up to tens of thousands of VLANS needed to be protected would not be economically efficient using manual processes and manual configuration.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] The gap between legacy honeypots and modern deception technology has diminished over time and will continue to do so.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Modern honeypots constitute the low end of the deception technology space today.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Traditional cyber defense technologies such as firewalls and endpoint security seek primarily to defend a perimeter, but they cannot do so with 100% certainty.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Heuristics may find an attacker within the network, but often generate so many alerts that critical alerts are missed.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] In a large enterprise, the alert volume may reach millions of alerts per day.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Security operations personnel cannot process most of the activity easily, yet it only takes one successful penetration to compromise an entire network.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] This means cyber-attackers can penetrate these networks and move unimpeded for months, stealing data and intellectual property.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology produces alerts that are the end product of a binary process.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Probability is essentially reduced to two values: 0% and 100%.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Any party that seeks to identify, ping, enter, view any trap or utilizes a lure is immediately identified as malicious by this behavior because anyone touching these traps or lures should not be doing so.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] This certainty is an advantage over the many extraneous alerts generated by heuristics and probability-based.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Best practice shows that deception technology is not a stand-alone strategy.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Deception technology is an additional compatible layer to the existing defense-in-depth cyber defense.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] Partner integrations make it most useful.
[src:honeypot/deception-technology] The goal is to add protection for the most advanced and sophisticated human attackers that will successfully penetrate the perimeter.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The Honeynet Project began in 1999 as a mailing list to a select few.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The group expanded and officially dubbed itself as The Honeynet Project in June 2000.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The project includes dozens of active chapters around the world, including Brazil, Indonesia, Greece, India, Mexico, Iran, Australia, Ireland, and many in the United States.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The Honeynet Project volunteers collaborate on security research efforts covering data analysis approaches, security tools development, and gathering data about hackers and malicious software.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The group's research provides sensitive information regarding attackers.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] This includes their motives, communication methods, attack timelines, and actions following a system attack.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] This information is provided through Know Your Enemy white papers, The Project blog posts, and Scan of the Month Forensic challenges.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The project uses unmodified computers with the same specifications, operating systems and security as those used by many companies.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] These computer production systems are added online and the network of volunteers scans the network for attacks or suspicious activity.
[src:honeypot/honeynet-project] The findings are published on the company site for public viewing and knowledge.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] In computer terminology, a **honeypot** is a computer security mechanism set to detect, deflect, or, in some manner, counteract attempts at unauthorized use of information systems.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Generally, a honeypot consists of data (for example, in a network site) that appears to be a legitimate part of the site which contains information or resources of value to attackers.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] It is actually isolated, monitored, and capable of blocking or analyzing the attackers.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] This is similar to police sting operations, colloquially known as "baiting" a suspect.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The main use for this network decoy is to distract potential attackers from more important information and machines on the real network, learn about the forms of attacks they can suffer, and examine such attacks during and after the exploitation of a honeypot.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] It provides a way to prevent and see vulnerabilities in a specific network system.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] A honeypot is a decoy used to protect a network from present or future attacks.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honeypots derive their value from the use by attackers.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] If not interacted with, the honeypot has little to no value.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honeypots can be used for everything from slowing down or stopping automated attacks, capturing new exploits, to gathering intelligence on emerging threats or early warning and prediction.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honeypots can be classified based on their deployment (use/action) and based on their level of involvement.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Recently, a new market segment called deception technology has emerged using basic honeypot technology with the addition of advanced automation for scale.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Deception technology addresses the automated deployment of honeypot resources over a large commercial enterprise or government institution.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] A malware honeypot is a decoy designed to intentionally attract malicious software.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] It does this by imitating a vulnerable system or network, such as a web server.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The honeypot is intentionally set up with security flaws that look to invite these malware attacks.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Once attacked, IT teams can then analyze the malware to better understand where it comes from and how it acts.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Spammers abuse vulnerable resources such as open mail relays and open proxies.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] These are servers that accept e-mail from anyone on the Internet—including spammers—and send it to its destination.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Some system administrators have created honeypot programs that masquerade as these abusable resources to discover spammer activity.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] There are several capabilities such honeypots provide to these administrators, and the existence of such fake abusable systems makes abuse more difficult or risky.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honeypots can be a powerful countermeasure to abuse from those who rely on very high-volume abuse (e.g., spammers).
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] These honeypots can reveal the abuser's IP address and provide bulk spam capture (which enables operators to determine spammers' URLs and response mechanisms).
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The apparent source may be another abused system.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Spammers and other abusers may use a chain of such abused systems to make detection of the original starting point of the abuse traffic difficult.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] This in itself is indicative of the power of honeypots as anti-spam tools.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] In the early days of anti-spam honeypots, spammers, with little concern for hiding their location, felt safe testing for vulnerabilities and sending spam directly from their own systems.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honeypots made the abuse riskier and more difficult.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Spam still flows through open relays, but the volume is much smaller than in 2001-02.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] While most spam originates in the U.S., spammers hop through open relays across political boundaries to mask their origin.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honeypot operators may use intercepted relay tests to recognize and thwart attempts to relay spam through their honeypots.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] "Thwart" may mean "accept the relay spam but decline to deliver it." Honeypot operators may discover other details concerning the spam and the spammer by examining the captured spam messages.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Open-relay honeypots include Jackpot, written in Java by Jack Cleaver; *smtpot.py*, written in Python by Karl A.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The *Bubblegum Proxypot* is an open-source honeypot (or "proxypot").
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] An email address that is not used for any other purpose than to receive spam can also be considered a spam honeypot.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Compared with the term "spamtrap", the term "honeypot" might be more suitable for systems and techniques that are used to detect or counterattack probes.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] With a spamtrap, spam arrives at its destination "legitimately"—exactly as non-spam email would arrive.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] An amalgam of these techniques is Project Honey Pot, a distributed, open-source project that uses honeypot pages installed on websites around the world.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] These honeypot pages disseminate uniquely tagged spamtrap email addresses and spammers can then be tracked—the corresponding spam mail is subsequently sent to these spamtrap e-mail addresses.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Databases often get attacked by intruders using SQL injection.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] As such activities are not recognized by basic firewalls, companies often use database firewalls for protection.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Some of the available SQL database firewalls provide/support honeypot architectures so that the intruder runs against a trap database while the web application remains functional.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Industrial Control Systems (ICS) are often the target of cyberattacks.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] One of the main targets within ICS are Programmable Logic Controllers.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] In order to understand intruders' techniques in this context, several honeypots have been proposed.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Conpot is a low interaction honeypot capable of simulation Siemens PLCs.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] HoneyPLC is a medium interaction honeypot that can simulate Siemens, Rockwell and other PLC brands.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Just as honeypots are weapons against spammers, honeypot detection systems are spammer-employed counter-weapons.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] This is an unusual circumstance in software; a situation in which "versionitis" (a large number of versions of the same software, all differing slightly from each other) can be beneficial.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] There's also an advantage in having some easy-to-detect honeypots deployed.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Fred Cohen, the inventor of the Deception Toolkit, argues that every system running his honeypot should have a deception port which adversaries can use to detect the honeypot.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Cohen believes that this might deter adversaries.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The goal of honeypots is to attract and engage attackers for a sufficiently long period to obtain high-level Indicators of Compromise (IoC) such as attack tools and Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs).
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Thus, a honeypot needs to emulate essential services in the production network and grant the attacker the freedom to perform adversarial activities to increase its attractiveness to the attacker.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Although the honeypot is a controlled environment and can be monitored by using tools such as honeywall, attackers may still be able to use some honeypots as pivot nodes to penetrate production systems.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The second risk of honeypots is that they may attract legitimate users due to a lack of communication in large-scale enterprise networks.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] For example, the security team who applies and monitors the honeypot may not disclose the honeypot location to all users in time due to the lack of communication or the prevention of insider threats.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Two or more honeypots on a network form a *honey net*.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Typically, a honey net is used for monitoring a larger and/or more diverse network in which one honeypot may not be sufficient.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Honey nets and honeypots are usually implemented as parts of larger network intrusion detection systems.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] A *honey farm* is a centralized collection of honeypots and analysis tools.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The concept of the honey net first began in 1999 when Lance Spitzner, founder of the Honeynet Project, published the paper "To Build a Honeypot".
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] An early formulation of the concept, called "entrapment", is defined in FIPS 39 (1976) as "the deliberate planting of apparent flaws in a system for the purpose of detecting attempted penetrations or confusing an intruder about which flaws to exploit".
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The earliest honeypot techniques are described in Clifford Stoll's 1989 book *The Cuckoo's Egg*.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] One of the earliest documented cases of the cybersecurity use of a honeypot began in January 1991.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] On January 7, 1991, while he worked at AT&T Bell Laboratories Bill Cheswick observed a criminal hacker, known as a cracker, attempting to obtain a copy of a password file.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] Cheswick wrote that he and colleagues constructed a "chroot "Jail" (or "roach motel")" which allowed them to observe their attacker over a period of several months.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] In 2017, Dutch police used honeypot techniques to track down users of the darknet market Hansa.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The metaphor of a bear being attracted to and stealing honey is common in many traditions, including Germanic, Celtic, and Slavic.
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] A common Slavic word for the bear is *medved* "honey eater".
[src:honeypot/honeypot-computing] The tradition of bears stealing honey has been passed down through stories and folklore, especially the well known Winnie the Pooh.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:honeypot/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware poses serious threats to individuals and businesses on the Internet.
[src:honeypot/malware] According to Symantec's 2018 Internet Security Threat Report (ISTR), the number of malware variants increased to 669,947,865 in 2017, which is twice as many malware variants as in 2016.
[src:honeypot/malware] Cybercrime, which includes malware attacks as well as other crimes committed by computer, was predicted to cost the global economy US$6 trillion in 2021, and is increasing at a rate of 15% per year.
[src:honeypot/malware] Since 2021, malware has been designed to target computer systems that run critical infrastructure such as the electricity distribution network.
[src:honeypot/malware] The defense strategies against malware differ according to its type, but most can be prevented by installing antivirus software or firewalls, applying regular patches, securing networks, creating backups, and isolating infected systems.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware can be designed to evade antivirus software detection algorithms.
[src:honeypot/malware] The notion of a self-reproducing computer program can be traced back to initial theories about the operation of complex automata.
[src:honeypot/malware] John von Neumann showed that in theory a program could reproduce itself.
[src:honeypot/malware] This constituted a plausibility result in computability theory.
[src:honeypot/malware] Fred Cohen experimented with computer viruses and confirmed Neumann's postulate and investigated other properties of malware such as detectability and self-obfuscation using rudimentary encryption.
[src:honeypot/malware] His 1987 doctoral dissertation was on the subject of computer viruses.
[src:honeypot/malware] The combination of cryptographic technology as part of the payload of the virus, exploiting it for attack purposes was initialized and investigated from the mid-1990s, and includes initial ransomware and evasion ideas.
[src:honeypot/malware] Before Internet access became widespread, viruses spread on personal computers by infecting executable programs or boot sectors of floppy disks.
[src:honeypot/malware] By inserting a copy of itself into the machine code instructions in these programs or boot sectors, a virus causes itself to be run whenever the program is run or the disk is booted.
[src:honeypot/malware] Early computer viruses were written for the Apple II and Mac, but they became more widespread with the dominance of the IBM PC and MS-DOS.
[src:honeypot/malware] The first IBM PC virus in the wild was a boot sector virus dubbed (c)Brain, created in 1986 by the Farooq Alvi brothers in Pakistan.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware distributors would trick the user into booting or running from an infected device or medium.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, a virus could make an infected computer add autorunnable code to any USB stick plugged into it.
[src:honeypot/malware] Anyone who then attached the stick to another computer set to autorun from USB would in turn become infected, and also pass on the infection in the same way.
[src:honeypot/malware] Older email software would automatically open HTML email containing potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:honeypot/malware] Users may also execute disguised malicious email attachments.
[src:honeypot/malware] The *2018 Data Breach Investigations Report* by Verizon, cited by CSO Online, states that emails are the primary method of malware delivery, accounting for 96% of malware delivery around the world.
[src:honeypot/malware] The first worms, network-borne infectious programs, originated not on personal computers, but on multitasking Unix systems.
[src:honeypot/malware] The first well-known worm was the Morris worm of 1988, which infected SunOS and VAX BSD systems.
[src:honeypot/malware] Unlike a virus, this worm did not insert itself into other programs.
[src:honeypot/malware] Instead, it exploited security holes (vulnerabilities) in network server programs and started itself running as a separate process.
[src:honeypot/malware] This same behavior is used by today's worms as well.
[src:honeypot/malware] With the rise of the Microsoft Windows platform in the 1990s, and the flexible macros of its applications, it became possible to write infectious code in the macro language of Microsoft Word and similar programs.
[src:honeypot/malware] These *macro viruses* infect documents and templates rather than applications (executables), but rely on the fact that macros in a Word document are a form of executable code.
[src:honeypot/malware] Many early infectious programs, including the Morris Worm, the first internet worm, were written as experiments or pranks.
[src:honeypot/malware] Today, malware is used by both black hat hackers and governments to steal personal, financial, or business information.
[src:honeypot/malware] Today, any device that plugs into a USB port – even lights, fans, speakers, toys, or peripherals such as a digital microscope – can be used to spread malware.
[src:honeypot/malware] Devices can be infected during manufacturing or supply if quality control is inadequate.
[src:honeypot/malware] Since the rise of widespread broadband Internet access, malicious software has more frequently been designed for profit.
[src:honeypot/malware] Since 2003, the majority of widespread viruses and worms have been designed to take control of users' computers for illicit purposes.
[src:honeypot/malware] Infected "zombie computers" can be used to send email spam, to host contraband data such as child pornography, or to engage in distributed denial-of-service attacks as a form of extortion.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware is used broadly against government or corporate websites to gather sensitive information, or to disrupt their operation in general.
[src:honeypot/malware] Further, malware can be used against individuals to gain information such as personal identification numbers or details, bank or credit card numbers, and passwords.
[src:honeypot/malware] Beyond its use in criminal enterprises, malware has also been deployed as a tool for sabotage, often driven by political objectives.
[src:honeypot/malware] A notable example is Stuxnet, which was engineered to interfere with specific industrial control systems.
[src:honeypot/malware] In other cases, politically motivated malware attacks have targeted entire networks, causing widespread disruption.
[src:honeypot/malware] In 2024, a botnet owner was arrested for engaging in a pay-per-install operation for financial gain.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware can be classified in numerous ways, and certain malicious programs may fall into two or more categories simultaneously.
[src:honeypot/malware] Broadly, software can be categorised into three types: (i) goodware; (ii) grayware and (iii) malware.
[src:honeypot/malware] A computer virus is software usually hidden within another seemingly harmless program that can produce copies of itself and insert them into other programs or files, and that usually performs a harmful action (such as destroying data).
[src:honeypot/malware] They have been likened to biological viruses.
[src:honeypot/malware] An example of this is a portable execution infection, a technique, usually used to spread malware, that inserts extra data or executable code into PE files.
[src:honeypot/malware] A computer virus is software that embeds itself in some other executable software (including the operating system itself) on the target system without the user's knowledge and consent and when it is run, the virus is spread to other executable files.
[src:honeypot/malware] A worm is a stand-alone malware software that *actively* transmits itself over a network to infect other computers and can copy itself without infecting files.
[src:honeypot/malware] These definitions lead to the observation that a virus requires the user to run an infected software or operating system for the virus to spread, whereas a worm spreads itself.
[src:honeypot/malware] Once malicious software is installed on a system, it is essential that it stays concealed, to avoid detection.
[src:honeypot/malware] Software packages known as *rootkits* allow this concealment, by modifying the host's operating system so that the malware is hidden from the user.
[src:honeypot/malware] Rootkits can prevent a harmful process from being visible in the system's list of processes, or keep its files from being read.
[src:honeypot/malware] Some types of harmful software contain routines to evade identification or removal attempts, not merely to hide themselves.
[src:honeypot/malware] A backdoor is a broad term for a computer program that allows an attacker persistent unauthorised remote access to a victim's machine often without their knowledge.
[src:honeypot/malware] The attacker typically uses another attack (such as a trojan, worm or virus) to bypass authentication mechanisms usually over an unsecured network such as the Internet to install the backdoor application.
[src:honeypot/malware] A backdoor can also be a side effect of a software bug in legitimate software that is exploited by an attacker to gain access to a victim's computer or network.
[src:honeypot/malware] The idea has often been suggested that computer manufacturers preinstall backdoors on their systems to provide technical support for customers, but this has never been reliably verified.
[src:honeypot/malware] Backdoors may be installed by Trojan horses, worms, implants, or other methods.
[src:honeypot/malware] A Trojan horse misrepresents itself to masquerade as a regular, benign program or utility in order to persuade a victim to install it.
[src:honeypot/malware] A Trojan horse usually carries a hidden destructive function that is activated when the application is started.
[src:honeypot/malware] The term is derived from the Ancient Greek story of the Trojan horse used to invade the city of Troy by stealth.
[src:honeypot/malware] Trojan horses are generally spread by some form of social engineering, for example, where a user is duped into executing an email attachment disguised to be unsuspicious, (e.g., a routine form to be filled in), or by drive-by download.
[src:honeypot/malware] While Trojan horses and backdoors are not easily detectable by themselves, computers may appear to run slower, emit more heat or fan noise due to heavy processor or network usage, as may occur when cryptomining software is installed.
[src:honeypot/malware] Cryptominers may limit resource usage or only run during idle times in an attempt to evade detection.
[src:honeypot/malware] Unlike computer viruses and worms, Trojan horses generally do not attempt to inject themselves into other files or otherwise propagate themselves.
[src:honeypot/malware] Modern Trojans are often disguised within legitimate-looking applications, making them particularly effective at bypassing basic user awareness and simple antivirus measures.
[src:honeypot/malware] In spring 2017, Mac users were hit by the new version of Proton Remote Access Trojan (RAT) trained to extract password data from various sources, such as browser auto-fill data, the Mac-OS keychain, and password vaults.
[src:honeypot/malware] Droppers are a sub-type of Trojans that solely aim to deliver malware upon the system that they infect with the desire to subvert detection through stealth and a light payload.
[src:honeypot/malware] It is important not to confuse a dropper with a loader or stager.
[src:honeypot/malware] A loader or stager will merely load an extension of the malware (for example a collection of malicious functions through reflective dynamic link library injection) into memory.
[src:honeypot/malware] The purpose is to keep the initial stage light and undetectable.
[src:honeypot/malware] A dropper merely downloads further malware to the system.
[src:honeypot/malware] Ransomware prevents a user from accessing their files until a ransom is paid.
[src:honeypot/malware] There are two variations of ransomware, being crypto ransomware and locker ransomware.
[src:honeypot/malware] Locker ransomware just locks down a computer system without encrypting its contents, whereas crypto ransomware locks down a system and encrypts its contents.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, programs such as CryptoLocker encrypt files securely, and only decrypt them on payment of a substantial sum of money.
[src:honeypot/malware] Lock-screens, or screen lockers is a type of "cyber police" ransomware that blocks screens on Windows or Android devices with a false accusation in harvesting illegal content, trying to scare the victims into paying up a fee.
[src:honeypot/malware] Jisut and SLocker impact Android devices more than other lock-screens, with Jisut making up nearly 60 percent of all Android ransomware detections.
[src:honeypot/malware] Encryption-based ransomware, like the name suggests, is a type of ransomware that encrypts all files on an infected machine.
[src:honeypot/malware] These types of malware then display a pop-up ad informing the user that their files have been encrypted and that they must pay (usually in Bitcoin) to recover them.
[src:honeypot/malware] Some examples of encryption-based ransomware are CryptoLocker and WannaCry.
[src:honeypot/malware] Some malware is used to generate money by click fraud, making it appear that the computer user has clicked an advertising link on a site, generating a payment from the advertiser.
[src:honeypot/malware] It was estimated in 2012 that about 60 to 70% of all active malware used some kind of click fraud, and 22% of all ad-clicks were fraudulent.
[src:honeypot/malware] Grayware is any unwanted application or file that can worsen the performance of computers and may cause security risks but which there is insufficient consensus or data to classify them as malware.
[src:honeypot/malware] Types of grayware typically include spyware, adware, fraudulent dialers, joke programs ("jokeware") and remote access tools.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, at one point, Sony BMG compact discs silently installed a rootkit on purchasers' computers with the intention of preventing illicit copying.
[src:honeypot/malware] Potentially unwanted programs (PUPs) are applications that would be considered unwanted despite often being intentionally downloaded by the user.
[src:honeypot/malware] PUPs include spyware, adware, and fraudulent dialers.
[src:honeypot/malware] Many security products classify unauthorised key generators as PUPs, although they frequently carry true malware in addition to their ostensible purpose.
[src:honeypot/malware] (2012) estimated that as much as 55% of key generators could contain malware and that about 36% malicious key generators were not detected by antivirus software.
[src:honeypot/malware] Some types of adware turn off anti-malware and virus protection; technical remedies are available.
[src:honeypot/malware] Programs designed to monitor users' web browsing, display unsolicited advertisements, or redirect affiliate marketing revenues are called spyware.
[src:honeypot/malware] Spyware programs do not spread like viruses; instead they are generally installed by exploiting security holes.
[src:honeypot/malware] They can also be hidden and packaged together with unrelated user-installed software.
[src:honeypot/malware] The Sony BMG rootkit was intended to prevent illicit copying; but also reported on users' listening habits, and unintentionally created extra security vulnerabilities.
[src:honeypot/malware] Antivirus software typically uses two techniques to detect malware: (i) static analysis and (ii) dynamic/heuristic analysis.
[src:honeypot/malware] Static analysis involves studying the software code of a potentially malicious program and producing a signature of that program.
[src:honeypot/malware] This information is then used to compare scanned files by an antivirus program.
[src:honeypot/malware] Because this approach is not useful for malware that has not yet been studied, antivirus software can use dynamic analysis to monitor how the program runs on a computer and block it if it performs unexpected activity.
[src:honeypot/malware] The aim of any malware is to conceal itself from detection by users or antivirus software.
[src:honeypot/malware] Detecting potential malware is difficult for two reasons.
[src:honeypot/malware] The first is that it is difficult to determine if software is malicious.
[src:honeypot/malware] The second is that malware uses technical measures to make it more difficult to detect it.
[src:honeypot/malware] An estimated 33% of malware is not detected by antivirus software.
[src:honeypot/malware] The most commonly employed anti-detection technique involves encrypting the malware payload in order to prevent antivirus software from recognizing the signature.
[src:honeypot/malware] Tools such as crypters come with an encrypted blob of malicious code and a decryption stub.
[src:honeypot/malware] The stub decrypts the blob and loads it into memory.
[src:honeypot/malware] Because antivirus does not typically scan memory and only scans files on the drive, this allows the malware to evade detection.
[src:honeypot/malware] Advanced malware has the ability to transform itself into different variations, making it less likely to be detected due to the differences in its signatures.
[src:honeypot/malware] Other common techniques used to evade detection include, from common to uncommon: (1) evasion of analysis and detection by fingerprinting the environment when executed; (2) confusing automated tools' detection methods.
[src:honeypot/malware] This allows malware to avoid detection by technologies such as signature-based antivirus software by changing the server used by the malware; (3) timing-based evasion.
[src:honeypot/malware] The use of existing binaries to carry out malicious activities is a technique known as LotL, or Living off the Land.
[src:honeypot/malware] This reduces the amount of forensic artifacts available to analyze.
[src:honeypot/malware] Recently these types of attacks have become more frequent with a 432% increase in 2017 and makeup 35% of the attacks in 2018.
[src:honeypot/malware] Such attacks are not easy to perform but are becoming more prevalent with the help of exploit-kits.
[src:honeypot/malware] A vulnerability is a weakness, flaw or software bug in an application, a complete computer, an operating system, or a computer network that is exploited by malware to bypass defences or gain privileges it requires to run.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, TestDisk 6.4 or earlier contained a vulnerability that allowed attackers to inject code into Windows.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, a common method is exploitation of a buffer overrun vulnerability, where software designed to store data in a specified region of memory does not prevent more data than the buffer can accommodate from being supplied.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware may provide data that overflows the buffer, with malicious executable code or data after the end; when this payload is accessed it does what the attacker, not the legitimate software, determines.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware can exploit recently discovered vulnerabilities before developers have had time to release a suitable patch.
[src:honeypot/malware] Even when new patches addressing the vulnerability have been released, they may not necessarily be installed immediately, allowing malware to take advantage of systems lacking patches.
[src:honeypot/malware] Sometimes even applying patches or installing new versions does not automatically uninstall the old versions.
[src:honeypot/malware] There are several ways the users can stay informed and protected from security vulnerabilities in software.
[src:honeypot/malware] Software providers often announce updates that address security issues.
[src:honeypot/malware] Common vulnerabilities are assigned unique identifiers (CVE IDs) and listed in public databases like the National Vulnerability Database.
[src:honeypot/malware] Tools like Secunia PSI, free for personal use, can scan a computer for outdated software with known vulnerabilities and attempt to update them.
[src:honeypot/malware] Firewalls and intrusion prevention systems can monitor the network traffic for suspicious activity that might indicate an attack.
[src:honeypot/malware] Users and programs can be assigned more privileges than they require, and malware can take advantage of this.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, of 940 Android apps sampled, one third of them asked for more privileges than they required.
[src:honeypot/malware] Apps targeting the Android platform can be a major source of malware infection but one solution is to use third-party software to detect apps that have been assigned excessive privileges.
[src:honeypot/malware] Some systems allow all users to make changes to the core components or settings of the system, which is considered over-privileged access today.
[src:honeypot/malware] This was the standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems, where there was no distinction between an *administrator* or *root*, and a regular user of the system.
[src:honeypot/malware] In some systems, non-administrator users are over-privileged by design, in the sense that they are allowed to modify internal structures of the system.
[src:honeypot/malware] In some environments, users are over-privileged because they have been inappropriately granted administrator or equivalent status.
[src:honeypot/malware] This can be because users tend to demand more privileges than they need, so often end up being assigned unnecessary privileges.
[src:honeypot/malware] Some systems allow code executed by a user to access all rights of that user, which is known as over-privileged code.
[src:honeypot/malware] This was also standard operating procedure for early microcomputer and home computer systems.
[src:honeypot/malware] Malware, running as over-privileged code, can use this privilege to subvert the system.
[src:honeypot/malware] Almost all currently popular operating systems, and also many scripting applications allow code too many privileges, usually in the sense that when a user executes code, the system allows that code all rights of that user.
[src:honeypot/malware] A credential attack occurs when a user account with administrative privileges is cracked and that account is used to provide malware with appropriate privileges.
[src:honeypot/malware] Typically, the attack succeeds because the weakest form of account security is used, which is typically a short password that can be cracked using a dictionary or brute force attack.
[src:honeypot/malware] Using strong passwords and enabling two-factor authentication can reduce this risk.
[src:honeypot/malware] With the latter enabled, even if an attacker can crack the password, they cannot use the account without also having the token possessed by the legitimate user of that account.
[src:honeypot/malware] It is estimated that approximately 83% of malware infections between January and March 2020 were spread via systems running Windows 10.
[src:honeypot/malware] This risk is mitigated by segmenting the networks into different subnetworks and setting up firewalls to block traffic between them.
[src:honeypot/malware] Anti-malware (sometimes also called antivirus) programs block and remove some or all types of malware.
[src:honeypot/malware] For example, Microsoft Security Essentials (for Windows XP, Vista, and Windows 7) and Windows Defender (for Windows 8, 10 and 11) provide real-time protection.
[src:honeypot/malware] The Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool removes malicious software from the system.
[src:honeypot/malware] Additionally, several capable antivirus software programs are available for free download from the Internet (usually restricted to non-commercial use).
[src:honeypot/malware] Tests found some free programs to be competitive with commercial ones.
[src:honeypot/malware] **Removal:** Anti-malware software programs can be used solely for detection and removal of malware software that has already been installed onto a computer.
[src:honeypot/malware] **Sandboxing:** Sandboxing confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations and isolating them from other applications on the host while limiting access to system resources.
[src:honeypot/malware] Browser sandboxing isolates web processes to prevent malware and exploits, enhancing security.
[src:honeypot/malware] Any time the operating system accesses a file, the on-access scanner checks if the file is infected or not.
[src:honeypot/malware] Typically, when an infected file is found, execution is stopped and the file is quarantined to prevent further damage with the intention to prevent irreversible system damage.
[src:honeypot/malware] Most AVs allow users to override this behaviour.
[src:honeypot/malware] This can have a considerable performance impact on the operating system, though the degree of impact is dependent on how many pages it creates in virtual memory.
[src:honeypot/malware] Sandboxing is a security model that confines applications within a controlled environment, restricting their operations to authorized "safe" actions and isolating them from other applications on the host.
[src:honeypot/malware] It also limits access to system resources like memory and the file system to maintain isolation.
[src:honeypot/malware] Browser sandboxing is a security measure that isolates web browser processes and tabs from the operating system to prevent malicious code from exploiting vulnerabilities.
[src:honeypot/malware] It helps protect against malware, zero-day exploits, and unintentional data leaks by trapping potentially harmful code within the sandbox.
[src:honeypot/malware] It involves creating separate processes, limiting access to system resources, running web content in isolated processes, monitoring system calls, and memory constraints.
[src:honeypot/malware] Inter-process communication (IPC) is used for secure communication between processes.
[src:honeypot/malware] Escaping the sandbox involves targeting vulnerabilities in the sandbox mechanism or the operating system's sandboxing features.
[src:honeypot/malware] While sandboxing is not foolproof, it significantly reduces the attack surface of common threats.
[src:honeypot/malware] Keeping browsers and operating systems updated is crucial to mitigate vulnerabilities.
[src:honeypot/malware] Website vulnerability scans check the website, detect malware, may note outdated software, and may report known security issues, in order to reduce the risk of the site being compromised.
[src:honeypot/malware] Structuring a network as a set of smaller networks, and limiting the flow of traffic between them to that known to be legitimate, can hinder the ability of infectious malware to replicate itself across the wider network.
[src:honeypot/malware] Software-defined networking provides techniques to implement such controls.
[src:honeypot/malware] However, malware can still cross the air gap in some situations, not least due to the need to introduce software into the air-gapped network and can damage the availability or integrity of assets thereon.
[src:honeypot/malware] Stuxnet is an example of malware that is introduced to the target environment via a USB drive, causing damage to processes supported on the environment without the need to exfiltrate data.
[src:honeypot/malware] AirHopper, BitWhisper, GSMem and Fansmitter are four techniques introduced by researchers that can leak data from air-gapped computers using electromagnetic, thermal and acoustic emissions.
[src:honeypot/malware] Utilizing bibliometric analysis, the study of malware research trends from 2005 to 2015, considering criteria such as impact journals, highly cited articles, research areas, number of publications, keyword frequency, institutions, and authors, revealed an annual growth rate of 34.1%.
[src:honeypot/malware] North America led in research output, followed by Asia and Europe.
[src:honeypot/malware] China and India were identified as emerging contributors.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a **threat actor** (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Threat actors are commonly analysed according to their motivations, resources, technical capability, access to systems, relationship to a target, and degree of connection to state authority.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] They may exploit vulnerabilities, conduct social engineering, steal or monetise data, disrupt operations, or support other actors who carry out such activity.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Because the term covers a wide range of actors, researchers and security organisations use taxonomies that distinguish between groups such as cybercriminals, state-linked actors, ideologically motivated actors, thrill seekers or trolls, insiders, and competitors.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Threat actor classifications are used in risk management, cyber threat intelligence, and incident response to connect observed behaviour with possible objectives and likely future activity.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The categories are not always mutually exclusive: the same actor may combine criminal, ideological, commercial, or state-linked motivations, and different organisations may use different names for similar actors.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In risk assessment, threat actor analysis is used to identify who or what may create, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat, and how that actor relates to the system being assessed.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Rausand and Haugen classify threat actors by their relationship to the system, distinguishing between internal and external actors, and by intent, distinguishing between intentional and unintentional actors.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Threat actor classification may also support incident investigation.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Rogers argued that actor categories could be inferred from observable case points, such as tools used, messages left, data targeted, forensic knowledge, and the degree of damage, allowing investigators to assess likely motivation and skill level.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Later work similarly linked actor classification to operational analysis.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Chng, Lu, Kumar and Yau proposed a framework connecting hacker types, motivations and typical strategies, arguing that observed behaviour before or during an attack can help analysts infer the likely type of actor involved.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] At the strategic level, actor analysis may consider an actor's resources, capabilities, degree of state involvement, motivations and objectives.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Its 2026 report argued that these actors vary in resources, technical sophistication and relationships with states, making it traditional distinctions between state, civilian combatant roles, and legitimate and illegitimate conduct harder to apply.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Early taxonomies classified hackers by activity, skill, motivation, or criminal profile.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Landreth proposed six categories based on activity: novice, student, tourist, crasher, and thief.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Hollinger classified computer misuse into pirates, browsers, and crackers, describing a progression from less-skilled activity to more technically serious offences.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Chantler used attributes including activity, skill, knowledge, motivation, and duration of involvement to distinguish between an elite group, neophytes, and "losers and lamers".
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Parker proposed seven profiles of cybercriminals: pranksters, hacksters, malicious hackers, personal problem solvers, career criminals, extreme advocates, and malcontents, addicts, and irrational or incompetent people.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In 2000, Marc Rogers proposed a taxonomy of hackers with seven, non-mutually-exclusive categories: newbie/tool kit users, cyber-punks, internals, coders, old guard hackers, professional criminals, and cyber-terrorists.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Rausand and Haugen distinguish between internal and external threat actors, and between intentional and unintentional threat actors.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Internal actors have some relationship with, access to, or position inside the system or organisation, while external actors operate from outside it.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Intentional actors seek to create, exploit, or support a threat event, whereas unintentional actors may cause or enable a threat event through error, negligence, accident, or lack of awareness.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Rogers later revised his hacker taxonomy into Novices, Cyber-punks, Internals, Petty Thieves, Virus Writers, Old Guard hackers, Professional Criminals, Information Warriors, and, more tentatively, Political Activists.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In the model, motivation is grouped into four broad domains: curiosity, notoriety, revenge, and financial gain.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] A 2022 review by Chng, Lu, Kumar and Yau examined 11 hacker typologies published over three decades and proposed a unified framework linking hacker types, motivations, and strategies.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The framework identified 13 hacker types and seven motivations, and argued that observed strategies during an attack can help analysts infer the likely type of actor involved.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Taxonomies of threat actors by governments are much more likely to include state-level threat actors.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] NIST treats threat-source identification as part of the risk-assessment process, alongside identifying threat events, vulnerabilities, likelihood and impact.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In the EU, European Union Agency for Cybersecurity publishes the annual *ENISA Threat Landscape*, which analyses cyber incidents and adversary behaviour affecting the European Union.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The 2025 report analysed selected incidents from the previous year and grouped activity around cybercrime, state-aligned activity, foreign information manipulation and interference, and hacktivism.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In ENISA's 2025 analysis, hacktivist activity dominated reporting, representing almost 80% of recorded incidents and consisting mainly of low-level distributed denial-of-service operations.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] ENISA also reported increasing convergence between hacktivism, cybercrime and state-nexus activity, including state-aligned use of hacktivist personas, hacktivist adoption of ransomware, and false-flag or impersonation activity.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Canada defines threat actors as states, groups, or individuals who aim to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability with malicious intent.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] A threat actor must be trying to gain access to information systems to access or alter data, devices, systems, or networks.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The Japanese government's National Centre of Incident Readiness and Strategy (NISC) was established in 2015 to create a "free, fair and secure cyberspace" in Japan.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The NICS created a cybersecurity strategy in 2018 that outlines nation-states and cybercrime to be some of the most key threats.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] It also indicates that terrorist usage of the cyberspace needs to be monitored and understood.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The Security Council of the Russian Federation published the cyber security strategy doctrine in 2016.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] This strategy highlights the following threat actors as a risk to cyber security measures: nation-state actors, cyber criminals, and terrorists.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Threat actors use techniques like Social engineering (security), and Phishing, alongside technical exploits like Cross-site scripting, SQL injection, and denial-of-service attacks.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] In practice, actor categories may overlap (Edward Snowden for example), and the same activity may combine features associated with hacktivism, cybercrime and state-linked operations.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] The lines between hacktivism, cybercrime and state-nexus activity had continued to blur, with shared toolsets, overlapping methods, fake personas, hacktivist adoption of ransomware, and cybercriminal or state-linked actors masquerading as other groups.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] Threat actor analysis also has limits as a risk-management method.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] NIST notes that risk assessments depend on their purpose, scope, assumptions, constraints, information sources, risk model and analytic approach, and that assessments are tied to particular time frames and organisational contexts.
[src:honeypot/threat-actor] NIST also warns that simple threat-vulnerability pairing may be undesirable or problematic where there are many threats and vulnerabilities, and recommends using risk scenarios to address some of those limitations.
